,"Europe":"Europe","Picardie, Aisne, Picardie, France":"Picardie, France","St Sauveur, Manche, Normandy, France":"Saint-Sauveur-la-Pommeraye, Manche, Normandy, France","Pont Audemer, Eure, Normandy, France":"Pont-Audemer, Eure, Normandy, France","Normandy, France":"Normandy, France","Avranches, Manche, Normandy, France":"Avranches, Manche, Normandy, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Haye","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Hans, Helmut, Willi.","North German, East Frisian, and Dutch: from a personal name, Frisian <i>Hajo</i>, ancient Germanic <i>Haio</i>; or from a short form of the female name <i>Hadewig</i>, composed of the elements <i>hadu</i> ‘battle, strife’ + <i>wīg</i> ‘war’.","German: variant of   Hey   4, 5."],"variants":[{"name":"Deshayes","meanings":["French: topographic name for someone who lived by an enclosure, from the plural of Old French <i>haye</i> ‘hedge’ (see   Haye   and   Hayes  ), with fused preposition and definite article <i>des</i> ‘from the’; or a habitational name denoting someone from Les Hayes, the name of several places in various parts of France. Compare   Deshaies  ."]},{"name":"Hayenga","meanings":["East Frisian: patronymic from the personal name <i>Hajo</i> (see   Haye   1). It is formed with the suffix <i>-enga</i>, a variant of <i>-inga</i> (from the patronymic suffix <i>-ing</i> and genitive plural ending <i>-a</i>)."]},{"name":"Hey","meanings":["English (Yorkshire and Lancashire): variant of   Hay  .","Dutch: variant, mostly Americanized (or archaic) and Flemish, of <b>Heij</b>, a topographic name for someone who lived on a heath, Dutch <i>hei</i>, <i>heide</i>.","German: metonymic occupational name for a grower or mower of grass, from Middle High German <i>höu</i> ‘grass, hay’."]},{"name":"Hayen","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Alphonse.  German Heinz, Wilhelm.","Flemish, East Frisian, and North German: patronymic from   Haye   1."]}]},{"name":"Sir","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Old Norse, originally a byname meaning ‘bride, wife’; in mythology the name of Thor's golden-haired wife."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Ranulf","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old Norse personal name, <i>Reginulfr</i>, derived from <i>regin</i> ‘advice, decision’ + <i>úlfr</i> ‘wolf’. This was introduced into Scotland and northern England by Scandinavian settlers in the early Middle Ages and modern use is largely confined to these areas."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Ranulf Senesha Haye was born in 1043, in Normandy, France, his father, Richard Thurstain de la Haye Haldup, was 21 and his mother, Emma Anne de Conteville, was 49. He had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Olivia Albini. He died in 1123, in Jerusalem, Jerusalem, Palestine, at the age of 80."},"et":{"1043–1123":"1043–1123","1047–1087":"1047–1087","1045–1087":"1045–1087","1123–1169":"1123–1169","1066–1095":"1066–1095","1070–1094":"1070–1094","1022–1101":"1022–1101","0994–1087":"0994–1087","1066":"1066","1022":"1022","1043":"1043","1087":"1087","1095":"1095","1094":"1094","1070":"1070","0994":"0994","1169":"1169","1047":"1047","1123":"1123","1101":"1101","1045":"1045","23 July 1101":"23. juuli 1101","16 June 1087":"16. juuni 1087","Jerusalem, Jerusalem, Palestine":"Jerusalem, Jerusalem, Palestiina","Europe":"Europe","Picardie, Aisne, Picardie, France":"Picardie, Prantsusmaa","St Sauveur, Manche, Normandy, France":"Saint-Sauveur-la-Pommeraye, Manche, Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Pont Audemer, Eure, Normandy, France":"Pont-Audemer, Eure, Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Normandy, France":"Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Avranches, Manche, Normandy, France":"Avranches, Manche, Normandie, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1043–1123":"1043–1123","1047–1087":"1047